<section id="1project1">
    <div class="project1-main-container">
        <h1>Monitoring the Water Quality in Bhopal Region using Satellite Imagery and GIS Techniques</h1>
        <hr>
        <br>
        <div class="background">
            <div class="img-background">
                <img class="img-back" src="/images/bhopal-gas-tragedy_1557259202.jpg">
            </div>
            <div class="content-background">
                <h3>Background</h3>
                <hr class="hr-1">
                <br>
                <p>In the 1980s, Bhopal witnessed a catastrophic industrial disaster, highlighting the grave consequences of industrial pollution. The aftermath of the 1984 gas tragedy still plagues the region, notably affecting water quality. Toxic substances released from the Union Carbide India Limited (UCIL) pesticide plant have severely contaminated groundwater, surface water, and the city's lakes. Extensive testing revealed dangerous levels of pollutants like lead, mercury, cadmium, Gamma HCH, Lindane, Beta HCH, Styrene, Mercury, Alpha HCH, Alpha Naphthol, Phosgene, and Dichlorobenzene in nearby communities. Bhopal grapples with deteriorating lake water quality due to volatile organic compounds (VOCs), pesticides, herbicides, and Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, leading to aquatic life decline and rendering the waters unfit for recreation.</p>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        <div class="problem">
            <div class="content-problem">
                <h3>The Problem</h3>
                <hr class="hr-1">
                <br>
            <p>Bhopal, known as "The City of Lakes," is marked by an abundance of water bodies, but it bears the grim legacy of the Gas Tragedy. Surveys conducted by local campaign groups reveal the presence of six United Nations-banned persistent organic pollutants in the environment, posing severe threats to both the ecosystem and human health. This contamination now extends to 42 areas in Bhopal, with a distressing trend of intergenerational disabilities. Additionally, the release of methyl isocyanide during the Gas Tragedy has led to the formation of harmful byproducts when it reacts with water, including chloroform and carbon tetrachloride, far exceeding safety guidelines. A pressing need to investigate Bhopal's lakes emerges.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="img-problem">
                <img class="img-prob"src="/images/vile-dribbble.gif">
            </div>
            
        </div>
        <div class="goals">
            <div class="img-goal">
                <img class="img-g" src="/images/marketing-goals.gif">
            </div>
            <div class="content-goal">
                <h3>The Project Goals</h3>
                <hr class="hr-1">
                <br>
                <p>This study aims to develop a Machine Learning system for monitoring the water quality of multiple lakes in the Bhopal region using satellite imagery and GIS techniques. The objective is to assess the water quality, detect the probable causes of water pollution and predict the potential impacts of different pollution sources on the environment and human health. The study will use a combination of remote sensing techniques, image processing methods, and GIS tools to extract relevant information from satellite data. Additionally, the system will enable real-time monitoring of water quality, allowing for timely intervention in case of any deterioration in water quality.</p>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        <div class="tech">

            <div class="content-tech">
                <h3>Technologies Used</h3>
                <hr class="hr-1">
                <br>
            <p>Our water quality monitoring project utilizes cutting-edge technology, leveraging Google Earth Engine (GEE), a cloud-based platform, to analyze extensive geospatial data, including satellite imagery and datasets. GEE helps us detect water quality changes by analyzing spectral signatures, identifying pollution or environmental stress areas. We also employ Geographic Information System (GIS) techniques for in-situ sensor data collection and analysis, producing water quality parameter maps and predictive models. This GEE and GIS integration offers a comprehensive understanding of water quality dynamics, guiding effective environmental management. Our project brochure showcases insights from monitoring lakes, demonstrating the power of these technologies in safeguarding water resources.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="img-tech">
                <img class="img-t" src="https://softflow.ca/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/cloud_computing.gif">
            </div>
        </div>
